At the time of the American Revolution, brigadiers in the British Army were NOT general officers, rather they were "temporary" appointments for certain colonels and lieutenant colonels assigned to command of "brigades," a group of regiments and battalions of a single "arm." As such, said "brigadiers" were effectively "super colonels" vice general officers. Theoretically general officers commanded "divisions" and larger units consisting of "combined arms."
